Thousands are expected to march to the Union Buildings on Wednesday, calling for President Jacob Zuma to step down. Police commissioner Khomotso Phahlane says they anticipate a peaceful event. PRETORIA - Acting National Police Commissioner Khomotso Phahlane says they have no information of a proposed counter march to Wednesday s anti-Zuma demonstrations and they anticipate a peaceful event. Phahlane and Police Minister Fikile Mbalula gave a security update in Pretoria on Tuesday afternoon. Thousands of people are expected to gather at Church Square on Wednesday before marching to the Union Buildings, calling for President Jacob Zuma to step down. Lieutenant general Phahlane called on demonstrators to conduct themselves responsibly. We are looking forward to an orderly march tomorrow. We do not have any information on a countermarch at this stage. Minister Mbalula says the police will keep a close eye on the demonstration. Any form of violence will force the hand of the police in terms of dealing with those elements. He also urged people to respect the rights of those who do not want to participate in the protest. (Edited by Winnie Theletsane)